class Animal {    
    Animal() { 
        System.out.println("An animal is created"); 
    }    
}    

class Dog extends Animal {    
    Dog(){    
        System.out.println("A dog is created");     
    }    
}    

class Main {    
    public static void main(String args[]) {    
        Dog d = new Dog();    
    }    
}
---------------
Execution Flow (Step by Step)
Step 1ï¸âƒ£

Program starts from:

main()

Step 2ï¸âƒ£

This line runs:

Dog d = new Dog();


Now object creation starts.

Step 3ï¸âƒ£

Before Dog() constructor runs,
Java automatically calls parent constructor first.

Internally Java adds:

super();


So actual Dog constructor becomes:

Dog() {
    super();   // automatically added
    System.out.println("A dog is created");
}

Step 4ï¸âƒ£

Now execution order:

Animal() constructor runs
â†’ prints:

An animal is created


Then Dog() constructor runs
â†’ prints:

A dog is created

âœ… Final Output
An animal is created
A dog is created

ğŸ”¥ Important Rule (Very Interview Important)

ğŸ‘‰ Parent class constructor runs first.
ğŸ‘‰ Then child class constructor runs.
ğŸ‘‰ super() is automatically inserted by compiler.

ğŸ¯ Why?

Because:

Child class inherits parent properties.

So parent must be initialized first.

ğŸ”¥ Visual Flow
main()
   â†“
new Dog()
   â†“
Animal() constructor
   â†“
Dog() constructor

ğŸ¯ Interview One-Line Answer

â€œWhen a child class object is created, the parent class constructor is executed first due to implicit super() call.â€
